    },
    {
        "content": "<p>That is some amazing black magic. I'm still trying to parse in my brain what exactly is going on here. How do I have no base case any longer?</p>",
        "id": 534558549,
        "sender_full_name": "Ryan Smith",
        "timestamp": 1755204947
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"130170\">Ryan Smith</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/113489-new-members/topic/Induction.20where.20the.20base.20case.20is.201.20not.200/near/534558549\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>That is some amazing black magic. I'm still trying to parse in my brain what exactly is going on here. How do I have no base case any longer?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>you don't need a base case for this kind of induction</p>",
        "id": 534558720,
        "sender_full_name": "Aaron Liu",
        "timestamp": 1755205012
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>For strong induction, the base case is implied, because when n = 0 (or 1 for your particular theorem), ih becomes \"useless\", as its condition can never be fulfilled</p>",
        "id": 534558861,
        "sender_full_name": "Weiyi Wang",
        "timestamp": 1755205078
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Ok right, so we implicitly handle it when the quantifier is quantifying over nothing</p>\n<p>More generally, what does generalize actually do? I thought I understood from a tutorial but now I think I do not.</p>",
        "id": 534559023,
        "sender_full_name": "Ryan Smith",
        "timestamp": 1755205158
